Title: Making Sense of the Middle East: Robin Wright in Conversation with Ralph Buultjens
ShortDesc: An award-winning historian and political correspondent, Robin Wright has reported from more than 140 countries on six continents for The Washington Post, The Los Angeles Times, The New York Times Magazine, amongst others, and is a regular contributor to The New Yorker.

Title: Sibling Rivalry: How to Keep the Peace at Home
ShortDesc: While many kids are lucky enough to become best of friends with their sibling, it is normal for siblings to fight, at least some of the time.

Title: Navigating the US Health Care System
ShortDesc: Health care in the U.S. faces an imperative for change. Americans are living longer and getting sicker.

Title: The Looks of Love: 50 Moments in Fashion That Inspired Romance
ShortDesc: Join fashion authority Hal Rubenstein as he showcases the seminal moments in film and television, and on the runway and red carpet, that have forever changed the way we look at love.

Title: Psychobiography with Dr. Gail Saltz: On Lady Bird and Lyndon Johnson with Betty Boyd Caroli
ShortDesc: Despite being perceived as a plain Jane who was married for her money, it turns out Lady Bird Johnson is arguably one of the most influential First Ladies in presidential history.

Title: Improve your Memory, Concentration, Mood and Well-Being
ShortDesc: How do you combine the cognitive science behind memory, sleep and stress to care for your brain?

Title: The President and the Apprentice: Eisenhower and Nixon, 1952-1961
ShortDesc: More than half a century after Eisenhower left office, the history of his presidency is so clouded by myth, partisanship and outright fraud that most people have little understanding of how Ike’s administration worked or what it accomplished.

Title: Landscape/Architecture: A Design Dream Team
ShortDesc: The design dream team of landscape architect Edmund Hollander and architect Thomas A. Kligerman pull aside the curtain on what it really takes to create a beautifully integrated home—from the inside out, and the outside in.

Title: American Organic: A Cultural History of Farming, Gardening, Shopping and Eating
ShortDesc: Organic farming is no longer a niche movement for humus-loving hippies.

Title: Becoming Richard Pryor
ShortDesc: Raised by an abusive grandmother in his family’s brothels, Richard Pryor may have been the most unlikely star in Hollywood history.

Title: Inside the Jewish Museum’s Unorthodox: A Talk and Tour
ShortDesc: This November, the Jewish Museum will present Unorthodox, a large-scale group exhibition featuring over 50 contemporary artists from around the world whose practices mix forms and genres without concern for artistic conventions.

Title: Pain-Free: A Healthy Neck and Back
ShortDesc: Dr. Michael Sein, a physiatrist at New York-Presbyterian Hospital/Weill Cornell Medical Center, explains the causes of herniated discs, sprains and muscle spasms and discusses treatments.

Title: Photographing Dancers in Motion
ShortDesc: Legendary dance photographer Lois Greenfield captures the grace and athleticism of some of the most talented dancers of our generation.

Title: Painting Central Park
ShortDesc: Central Park has often been called one of America's greatest works of art.

Title: A Guest at the Shooters’ Banquet
ShortDesc: Three years ago, Rita Gabis discovered an unthinkable dimension to her family story: from 1941 to 1943, her grandfather had been chief of security police under the Gestapo in the Lithuanian town of Sˇvencˇionys, where eight thousand Jews were murdered over three days in 1941.

Title: Skincare 101
ShortDesc: Leading dermatologist Dr. Ellen Marmur shares her expertise in what works and what doesn’t when it comes to skin health and your everyday skin care routine.

Title: On the Music of Fred and Ginger
ShortDesc: Cole Porter’s “Night And Day”, Jerome Kern’s “The Way You Look Tonight” and Irving Berlin’s “Cheek to Cheek.”

Title: On Bob Hope
ShortDesc: Bob Hope achieved top-rated success in every mass-entertainment medium, from vaudeville to television and everything in between.

Title: On Sammy Cahn
ShortDesc: Sammy Cahn wrote some of the most popular songs of the Great American Songbook, including more songs for Frank Sinatra than any other songwriter.

Title: 10 Proven, Easy Ways to Calm & Soothe Yourself without Food
ShortDesc: Learn 10 new ways to find calm during a hectic day that don't involve any calories whatsoever.

Title: The 9/11 Terror Cases and their Constitutional Challenges
ShortDesc: The terrorist attacks of 9/11 are indelibly etched into our memory. But they also created complex legal ramifications and heated debate that continues unabated on the limits of government power in the name of national security.

Title: Psychobiography with Dr. Gail Saltz: On Johannes Brahms with Jan Swafford
ShortDesc: Johannes Brahms is one of history’s most influential composers.

Title: The Takedown of a $100 Million Chinese Software Pirate
ShortDesc: Digital pirates overseas steal and resell hundreds of billions of dollars in American intellectual property each year.

Title: Alzheimer’s Disease: Running in the Family
ShortDesc: We are living longer and healthier than all previous generations, but every 70 seconds someone is diagnosed with Alzheimer’s disease.

Title: Inventing Impressionism
ShortDesc: Join Milton Esterow, former editor and publisher of ARTnews, to understand how Impressionism became the most popular art style in the world and grew to become the wealthy collectors’ ultimate status symbol.

Title: A Renaissance Genius: Michelangelo in Rome
ShortDesc: From painting to sculpture, from theoretical treatises to architecture, Michelangelo challenged the conventions of his time and left the world with signature masterpieces.

Title: Social Media in the American War Zone
ShortDesc: For most of us, clicking “like” on social media has become fairly routine.

Title: Michael Anthony Talks Vegetables! with John T. Edge
ShortDesc: James Beard Outstanding Chef in the USA-winner Michael Anthony of Gramercy Tavern and Untitled, the restaurant at the new Whitney Museum, shares his secrets for creating delicious fresh flavors from his new book, V Is for Vegetables.

Title: Hartwood: Bright Wild Flavors from the Edge of the Yucatán
ShortDesc: Five years ago, Eric Werner and Mya Henry left New York City to build their dream restaurant in the one-road town of Tulum, Mexico.

Title: François Payard Talks Cookies with Michael Laiskonis
ShortDesc: Pastry chef François Payard shares some of his all-time favorite cookie recipes featured in Payard Cookies—the bestsellers at his popular New York City patisseries and cafés, the recipes he learned from his father, and the ones he makes at home.

Title: Dominique Crenn Talks with Kerry Diamond About Her Atelier
ShortDesc: Chef Dominique Crenn, the creative force behind San Francisco’s two Michelin-starred Atelier Crenn, talks about her highly anticipated first cookbook, Atelier Crenn: Metamorphosis of Taste with Cherry Bombe’s Kerry Diamond.

Title: Madhur Jaffrey: Vegetarian India with Karen Page
ShortDesc: No one knows Indian food like Madhur Jaffrey.

Title: John Leguizamo in Conversation
ShortDesc: John Leguizamo’s 30-year career in show business has included turns in movies such as Chef, Ride Along, Romeo + Juliet, Moulin Rouge! and Carlito’s Way and onstage in five award-winning one-man shows.

Title: Nathan Lane in Conversation with Joy Behar
ShortDesc: One of his generation’s most brilliant comic actors, the two-time Tony winner Nathan Lane joins us to talk about his life in theater.

Title: Politics and Pundits: Congressman Steve Israel with Chris Matthews
ShortDesc: We always knew Rep. Steve Israel had a funny side, but last December he “revealed his inner Jon Stewart,” according to the New York Daily News, with his novel The Global War on Morris.

Title: Judith Light in Conversation with Jeffrey Tambor
ShortDesc: On stage and screen, Judith Light makes interesting choices playing complicated and intriguing women.

Title: Celebrating Alvin Ailey: Robert Battle, Judith Jamison, Matthew Rushing and Rachael McLaren with Budd Mishkin
ShortDesc: Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater grew from a now-fabled performance in March 1958 at 92nd Street Y.

Title: Elvis Duran in Conversation with Rosanna Scotto
ShortDesc: What gets Elvis Duran up in the morning?

Title: An Evening with Jerry Saltz
ShortDesc: After being temporarily booted off Facebook for posting art historical images that “didn’t quite mesh with the social networking site’s regulations” (ARTNews), Jerry Saltz, New York magazine’s outrageous and influential art critic, joins us for what’s sure to be a spirited talk.

Title: Sir John Richardson and Gijs van Hensbergen: On Picasso
ShortDesc: Join legendary art connoisseur and Picasso biographer Sir John Richardson and his collaborator Gijs van Hensbergen for a lively discussion about Picasso’s life and work.

Title: Don McCullin with Sebastian Junger
ShortDesc: Don McCullin is one of the great photographers of our time.

Title: David Brooks and Mark Shields in Conversation with Jeff Greenfield: Election 2016
ShortDesc: When commentators of the caliber of syndicated columnist Mark Shields and The New York Times op-ed columnist David Brooks get together to discuss today’s major issues, you know you’re in for an illuminating and stimulating evening.

Title: Jon Meacham in Conversation with George Stephanopoulos
ShortDesc: The Pulitzer Prize-winning historian discusses his new biography of the 41st president, Destiny and Power with ABC News “This Week” host and chief anchor George Stephanopoulos.

Title: Bob Schieffer in Conversation with Norah O'Donnell
ShortDesc: Few people know more about politics than Bob Schieffer, the Washington insider who’s been on a first-name basis with key DC figures for decades.

Title: Peggy Noonan in Conversation with Joe Scarborough
ShortDesc: Peggy Noonan—one of our most astute political commentators and a speechwriter for the Reagan White House—is not known for mincing words.

Title: Ted Koppel in Conversation with Charlie Rose: Lights Out: A Cyberattack, A Nation Unprepared, Surviving the Aftermath
ShortDesc: When Ted Koppel issues a warning, you listen. The ABC News veteran who’s won every significant TV award (including 42 Emmys) tells us that a major cyber attack on America’s power grid is not only possible, but likely.

Title: Alex Gibney and Lawrence Wright with Janice Min, moderator
ShortDesc: Director Alex Gibney has been called “the most important documentarian of our time” (Esquire).

Title: Mary Beard on Ancient Rome
ShortDesc: “Beard’s popularizing bent is grounded in a deep knowledge of the arcane, and she gives new insight into the hoariest of topics,” wrote Rebecca Mead in The New Yorker.

Title: Dan Ariely and the Honest Truth about Dishonesty
ShortDesc: Just as he showed us how irrationality steers our decision-making, superstar behavioral economist Dan Ariely reveals that none of us is immune to cheating.

Title: Lisa Randall and Bill Nye the Science Guy
ShortDesc: The first female theoretical physicist tenured at Harvard, Lisa Randall makes ideas like string theory and quantum mechanics accessible to the rest of us in bestselling books like Knocking on Heaven’s Door and Warped Passages.

Title: Rabbi Lord Jonathan Sacks: Not in God’s Name—Confronting Religious Violence
ShortDesc: Rabbi Lord Jonathan Sacks, one of the most admired religious leaders of our time delivers a major address on how we can understand and confront religious violence.

ShortDesc: Join former NBC newsman and “Meet the Press” moderator David Gregory and religious scholar Erica Brown as they discuss issues of faith, identity and leadership in your personal and professional life.

Title: The Bonfire of the Vanities: Tom Wolfe and Preet Bharara with Thane Rosenbaum
ShortDesc: This comedy-drama starring Tom Hanks, Melanie Griffith and Bruce Willis explores the mix of ambition, racism, politics and greed in 1980s New York, when being a Master of the Universe defined the very meaning of Wall Street excess and entitlement.

Title: Simply Nigella: Nigella Lawson with Gabrielle Hamilton
ShortDesc: Nigella Lawson changed the way we think—and feel—about home cooking.

ShortDesc: George Gershwin traveled to Paris in 1928, intent on composing a new orchestral piece.

ShortDesc: For more than 15 years, 92Y audiences have relished the clarity and thoughtfulness Professor Ralph Buultjens brings to discussions of foreign affairs.

ShortDesc: Join the star chef, founder and co-owner of the wildly popular restaurant Mission Chinese Food to hear about his riotous new book that’s packed with recipes that embody his signature mash-up of “Chinese” food and American classics.

Title: Read Aloud: National Book Award Teen Press Conference
ShortDesc: At the annual National Book Awards Teen Press Conference, middle and high school students from New York City’s public and private schools play the role of reporters as they direct questions to the five Finalists for the 2015 National Book Award in Young People's Literature.

Title: Unorthodox Exhibitions: Hans Ulrich Obrist and Jens Hoffmann
ShortDesc: Born in May 1968 in Switzerland, Hans Ulrich Obrist is widely regarded as the most experimental and unconventional curator of his generation and is credited with radically altering the traditional understanding of exhibition-making.

ShortDesc: Graphic designer Milton Glaser, known for iconic work including the “I Love New York” logo and co-founding New York magazine, in conversation with New York design editor Wendy Goodman.

ShortDesc: Top Israeli espionage expert Michael Bar-Zohar is joined by Pulitzer Prize-winning investigative journalist Judith Miller for a riveting look inside the most daring and white-knuckle missions of the Israeli Special Forces, as told in his new book, No Mission Is Impossible.

Title: Adventures in Record Collecting: a Conversation and Listening Party with Dust & Grooves
ShortDesc: Photographer and vinyl champion Eilon Paz traveled around the world for 5 years from Brooklyn to West Africa interviewing record collectors in the most intimate of environments—their record rooms.

Title: General David Petraeus in Conversation with Vance Serchuk: National Security Challenges for the Next President
ShortDesc: See General David Petraeus talk with Vance Serchuk, an adviser to Senator Joe Lieberman, about national security challenges and election 2016.

ShortDesc: Enjoy some of Irving Berlin’s most memorable songs, including “White Christmas,” while hearing inside stories from special guest Robert Kimball.

Title: Aziz Ansari: "Master of None" Advance Screening and Conversation with Jon Hamm

Title: Funny People: Alan Zweibel in Conversation with Martin Short
ShortDesc: Join two comedic giants as they discuss their recent books and share stories from their incredible careers. A book selling and signing follows the program.

Title: Hoda Kotb and Andy Cohen in Conversation
ShortDesc: What's the right path for your personal journey? Have you ever asked yourself: Is it too late to do that thing that made me so happy when I was young? Am I where I belong?

Title: Larry Wilmore in Conversation
ShortDesc: What’s it like to take over one of TV’s most coveted slots? Pretty manageable if you’re Larry Wilmore, who’s brought a bold new voice to late-night—serving up equal doses of smart and funny on Comedy Central’s acclaimed “Nightly Show.”

Title: Seven Days of Genius: What’s Out There?
ShortDesc: Two top astrophysicists explain why we are in the Golden Age of cosmological exploration.

Title: Sally Mann in Conversation
ShortDesc: Sally Mann is considered one of the most influential photographers of her time. Join her for an intimate conversation about her book, her photography, the American South and her life’s work.

Title: Rod Stewart in Conversation with Hoda Kotb
ShortDesc: Don’t miss this chance to join two-time Rock and Roll Hall of Famer and global superstar for an intimate interview.

Title: Fashion Icons Special Event: Michael Bierut in Conversation with Fern Mallis
ShortDesc: Michael Bierut in Conversation with Fern Mallis, the man behind so much of the design we see every day in our city.

Title: A Conversation with Lewis Black Presented in Association with the New York Comedy Festival
ShortDesc: See comedian Lewis Black, the king of the angry rant, as he takes on American society and politics and looks back on his brilliant career.

Title: On Ronald Reagan: Jacob Weisberg in Conversation with Christopher Buckley
The Catskills: Its History and How It Changed America: Stephen Silverman in Conversation
ShortDesc: From the majesty of the landscape; refuge and home to poets and gangsters, tycoons and politicians, preachers and outlaws, musicians and spiritualists, outcasts and rebels. Author Stephen Silverman brings the Catskills to life in all of their intensity, beauty, vastness and lunacy.

Title: Pat & Jamie’s NYC
ShortDesc: NY1’s Pat Kiernan and Jamie Stelter, one of our favorite morning duos, bring their banter uptown this fall for a new series with special guests dishing on everything we love and love to hate about NYC.

Title: Parkinson’s Disease—Past, Present and Future
ShortDesc: Learn about recent advances in the treatment of Parkinson's disease with Mount Sinai Health System doctor Steven Frucht, MD.

Title: U.S. Foreign Policy & the 2016 Election
ShortDesc: A free-wheeling discussion with four of America’s most distinguished experts: Hudson Institute’s Walter Russell Mead, Foreign Affairs editor Gideon Rose, Foreign Policy editor David J. Rothkopf and Pulitzer Prize-winning columnist Bret Stephens of the Wall Street Journal.

Title: In Conversation with Paul Krugman: The State of the Economy
ShortDesc: As one of the world's leading economists, Professor Krugman's work as an Op-Ed columnist for The New York Times has so often explained in clear and concise terms the economic issues that affect us all—especially in these times of global uncertainty.

Title: Rocco DiSpirito in Conversation with Stacy London
ShortDesc: Rocco DiSpirito—James Beard Award-winning restaurateur, New York Times bestselling author, celebrity TV chef, health advocate—has done more to persuade America that healthy and delicious are not mutually exclusive than virtually any other chef on the planet.

Title: One Day University: The Genius of Mozart, Michelangelo and Shakespeare
ShortDesc: One Day University has teamed up with 92Y to present a special morning of fascinating lectures by three dynamic college professors renowned for their teaching.

Title: Sisters in Law: The Story of Sandra Day O’Connor and Ruth Bader Ginsburg
ShortDesc: Join author, lawyer and pundit Linda Hirshman and MSNBC reporter and author Irin Carmon as they tell the fascinating story of Sandra Day O'Connor and Ruth Bader Ginsburg, the first and second women to serve as Supreme Court justices.

Title: Slow Reading: A Doll’s House by Henrik Ibsen
ShortDesc: When was the last time you read a great work at a slow pace to really ingest its richness?

Title: Personal Histories: Reading Contemporary Memoirs
ShortDesc: This class explores contemporary memoirs by writers from diverse social backgrounds.

Title: Novels with a Social Conscience
ShortDesc: Discuss six outstanding novels: Of Mice and Men by John Steinbeck; The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter by Carson McCullers; Native Son by Richard Wright; What Makes Sammy Run? by Budd Schulberg; Tsotsi by Athol Fugard; and Of Love and Shadows by Isabel Allende.

Title: Great American Fiction
ShortDesc: Experience the creative genius of some of the nation’s most gifted authors, both past and present.

Title: Best of World Literature
ShortDesc: Enjoy the stunning work of these authors from around the world.

Title: Arguably, Some of the Best Books of the 20th Century
ShortDesc: The operative word here is “arguably.” Read the books, discuss their meaning, their message, and, of course, argue their merits (or demerits).

Title: Sunday Afternoon Reading Group
ShortDesc: After Labor Day, Sunday afternoons often become a time to sit back and read books that some consider substantial.

Title: Yusef Komunyakaa and Wendell Pierce
ShortDesc: Poet Yusef Komunyakaa and actor Wendell Pierce—both Louisiana natives—share a stage for the first time.

Title: David Mitchell
ShortDesc: Author of the acclaimed epics Cloud Atlas, The Bone Clocks and The Thousand Autumns of Jacob de Zoet, David Mitchell reads from his new novel, Slade House, a time-bending thriller he started as a Twitter story and could not let go of.

Title: John Irving
ShortDesc: John Irving explores fate and memory in his new novel, Avenue of Mysteries, which follows an old man on a journey to the Philippines and back into the dreams of his childhood.

Title: Kay Ryan
ShortDesc: Kay Ryan’s new book of poems is Erratic Facts.

Title: Claudia Rankine
ShortDesc: Poet Claudia Rankine reads from Citizen, her recent meditation on race in America, then sits for a conversation on art, trauma and social justice with Cleonie White and Sarah Stemp, clinicians from the William Alanson White Psychoanalytic Society.

Title: A Celebration of Yehuda Amichai

Title: László Krasznahorkai and Salman Rushdie
ShortDesc: A rare US appearance by László Krasznahorkai—the “contemporary Hungarian master of apocalypse,” wrote Susan Sontag. Salman Rushdie’s new novel is Two Years, Eight Months and Twenty-Eight Nights.

Title: A Celebration of Wisława Szymborska
ShortDesc: A celebration of the Polish Nobel Laureate upon publication of Map: Collected and Last Poems.

Title: Tessa Hadley and Jane Smiley
ShortDesc: Tessa Hadley’s new novel is The Past. Jane Smiley’s new novel is Golden Age.

Title: Garrison Keillor
ShortDesc: “Ah, seventy … your work is triumphant, you pee like a Palomino pony, and your imagination is more vivid than ever before,” writes Garrison Keillor.

Title: Howard Jacobson and James Shapiro
ShortDesc: Rediscover Shakespeare with two quick-witted storytellers renowned for their imagination and scholarship.

Title: Mary Karr and Helen Macdonald
ShortDesc: Mary Karr’s new book is The Art of the Memoir. Helen Macdonald is author of H is for Hawk.

Title: Susan Howe and Ben Lerner
ShortDesc: An evening with two poets also highly regarded for their prose.

Title: Anne Carson
ShortDesc: Anne Carson reads from FLOAT, her new book of poetry.

Title: Discovery/Boston Review Poetry Contest Winners' Reading
ShortDesc: The Joan Leiman Jacobson Poetry Prizes are presented by the 92Y Unterberg Poetry Center and Boston Review.

Title: Louise Erdrich and Anne Enright
ShortDesc: Erdrich’s new novel is LaRose. Enright’s The Green Road has been nominated for the Man Booker Prize.

Title: Olga Voronina on Nabokov’s Letters to Véra
ShortDesc: Now published for the first time in new translations by editors Brian Boyd and Olga Voronina, Nabokov’s Letters to Véra—his wife, muse and lifelong partner—tell a long and beguiling love story and document anew the creative energies of a brilliant artist who was always at work.

Title: Adam Gopnik on Anthony Trollope
ShortDesc: In celebration of Anthony Trollope’s bicentenary, Adam Gopnik pays tribute to one of his favorite novelists.

Title: David Orr on Robert Frost
ShortDesc: David Orr presents a cultural biography of Robert Frost’s famous poem in The Road Not Taken.

Title: On Proust with Benjamin Taylor
ShortDesc: Benjamin Taylor’s new biography of the master novelist is Proust: The Future’s Secret.

Title: On Charlotte Brontë with Claire Harman
ShortDesc: Claire Harman’s new biography of Charlotte Brontë—timed to her bicentenary—explores the life of a literary visionary and feminist trailblazer that contained all the drama and tragedy of the great Gothic novels (Jane Eyre, Villette, Shirley, The Professor) that it inspired.

Title: On William Blake with Leo Damrosch
ShortDesc: In Eternity’s Sunrise: The Imaginative World of William Blake, Leo Damrosch—acclaimed biographer of Swift, Rousseau and Toqueville—draws extensively on Blake’s poems, paintings, etchings and engravings to offer a generously illustrated account of Blake the man and Blake the visionary.

Title: Anne Heller on Hannah Arendt
ShortDesc: Hannah Arendt was one of the most gifted and provocative voices of her era.

Title: James McBride
ShortDesc: Author of the classic memoir The Color of Water, James McBride travels the country tracking the legend of James Brown in his new work of nonfiction, Kill ’Em and Leave.

Title: Nathaniel Mackey with Cathy Park Hong: A Live Paris Review Writers-at-Work Interview
ShortDesc: Over the years, the Poetry Center has teamed with The Paris Review to present numerous onstage conversations that have often led to Writers-at-Work interviews appearing in the magazine.

Title: Helen Vendler on Seamus Heaney
ShortDesc: In this seminar, we will take up poems from the three volumes Seamus Heaney completed between the 1995 Nobel Prize and his death in 2013.
